Q: Can TinyMCE convert image pasted as data to an upload? A: <p>to avoid duplicate image use <code>paste_preprocess</code> and replace the src URL.</p>
<p>paste image from other web page: <code>&lt;img src=&quot;http://url&quot; title=&quot;text&quot;&gt;</code></p>
<p>paste image from other application: <code>&lt;img src=&quot;blob:http://url&quot;&gt;</code></p>
<pre class="lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>tinymce.init({
    selector: '#editor',
    //paste_as_text: false, // important, unset or set to false
    paste_data_images: true,
    paste_preprocess: (editor, args) =&gt; {
        let image = args.content.match(/^&lt;img\ssrc=&quot;([^&quot;]+).+[^&gt;]+&gt;$/); // check if pasted data is image element
        if (image) {
            let srcUrl = image[1];
            // process the image
            let newUrl = processTheImage(srcUrl);
            args.content = args.content.replace(/src=&quot;[^&quot;]+/, `src=&quot;${newUrl}`)
        }
    },

})
</code></pre>

Q: Trying to implement collapsible/expandable rows in a table using only HTML and CSS A: <p>There is even simpler and in my opinion more elegant solution. My goal was to render the content within the table row itself, so that there is no change in experience - borders are same, row highlight is consistent, hover effects remain on the same row, etc.</p>
<p>The code below looks complicated, because I added transitions and borders, but the idea is simple:</p>
<ol>
<li>use <code>padding-bottom</code> to make space for a custom div</li>
<li>absolutely position the <code>div</code> to the parent <code>tr</code></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>and that's it!</li>
</ul>
<p><div class="snippet" data-lang="js" data-hide="true" data-console="false" data-babel="false" data-babel-preset-react="false" data-babel-preset-ts="false">
<div class="snippet-code snippet-currently-hidden">
<pre class="snippet-code-css lang-css prettyprint-override"><code>tr.expandable {
  &amp;&gt;td {
    transition-property: padding-bottom;
    transition-duration: 300ms;
  }

  /* This is the content that will slide in. */
  &amp; .expanding {
    display: none;
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    bottom: 0;
    width: 100%;
  }

  /* To trigger the effect use hover or class on a parent or the tr itself. */
  &amp;:hover, .expanded &amp;, &amp;.expanded {
    position: relative;

    &amp;&gt;td {
      padding-bottom: 2.5rem;
    }

    &amp; .expanding {
      display: block;
    }
  }
}

table {
  border-collapse: collapse;
  width: 100%;
}

tr {
  border: 1px solid black;
}</code></pre>
<pre class="snippet-code-html lang-html prettyprint-override"><code>&lt;table class="_try_expanded"&gt;
  &lt;tbody&gt;
    &lt;tr&gt;
      &lt;th&gt;1&lt;/th&gt;
      &lt;th&gt;2&lt;/th&gt;
    &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;tr class="expandable _try_expanded"&gt;
      &lt;td&gt;
        Hello
      &lt;/td&gt;
      &lt;td&gt;
        Hover me!
        &lt;div class="expanding"&gt;
          This will be visible only when expanded
        &lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;/td&gt;
    &lt;/tr&gt;
  &lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
</p>
